ewed black children as symbols of America’s possible future. The story of their lives, their work, and their friendship testifies to the imagination and activism of the free black community that shaped the national journey toward freedom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican American intellectualsvBiography. 0aAfrican AmericansxColonizationzAfricaxHistoryy19th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxCultural assimilationxHistoryy19th century. 0aAntislavery movementszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aFree blackszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlaveryzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh  a1863 riot.  aAddress to the Slaves.  aAfrican American.  aAfrican Civilization Society.  aAfrican colonization.  aAmerican Colonization Society.  aBlack abolitionist.  aBlack rebellion.  aCivil War.  aColored Orphan Asylum.  aFrederick Douglass.  aFree Produce Movement.  aHeads of the Colored People.  aHenry Highland Garnet.  aJames McCune Smith.  aJohn Brown.  aLincoln.  aMarxist.  aNew York African Free School.  aNew York Colored Orphan Asylum.  aNoyes Academy.  aThirteenth Amendment.  aUniversity of Glasgow.  aWeims family.  aabolitionism.  aantislavery.  acensus.  acolonization.  afreak shows.  amanhood.40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479877225.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479877225423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479877225/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles